<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900601-0169</DOCNO><DOCID>900601-0169.</DOCID><HL>   Hong Kong to Expand Issues</HL><DATE>06/01/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   FREST</CO><IN>BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)</IN><LP>   HONG KONG -- Hong Kong will expand its fledgling ExchangeFund bill program to include treasury instruments that arelonger than 13 weeks in duration, David Nendick, the colony'ssecretary for monetary affairs, said.   Mr. Nendick said that he is pleased with the dozen weeklyauctions of the tax-free bills to date, but that some changeswill be made after the initial program ends next Tuesday. &quot;Toenhance the effectiveness of the bills as money marketinstruments, bills of other maturities up to 12 months may beissued additionally from time to time,&quot; he said. Thegovernment began auctioning off the 13-week bills inmid-March to provide a mechanism to adjust liquidity in thesystem. About 3.5 billion Hong Kong dollars (US$444.9million) of bills have been offered in HK$300 millioninstallments.</LP><TEXT>   Hong Kong has had a steady stream of budget surpluses, soit doesn't need to rely on treasury debt issues for fiscalreasons. The auctions for Exchange Fund bills have found asteady local appetite and are regularly oversubscribed.</TEXT></DOC>